text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!Sign Language]]%0a%0a!Diversity in ASL%0a%0a:Author: kyuwonW%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aDiversity in ASL%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0a%0aOne misconception people have with sign languages is that it is universal. Just unifying the sign languages into one will result in less complication and make it easier for people to communicate internationally. However, sign languages are like spoken languages that evolve based on the interactions within the community. Having different sign languages in different parts of the world is a natural phenomenon.   %0a%0aCurrently, there are about 138 to 300 types of sign languages used. ASL, American Sign Language, is used predominantly in the United States and in parts of Canada. LSF(French Sign Language) provided a basis for ASL, along with the dutch, german, Irish, Brazilian, and so on.  Comparing ASL with JSL(Japanese Sign Language), JSL uses more fingerspelling and much more mouthing to distinguish different signs than ASL. But while differences in ASL and JSL were expected, Britain and Australia also have their own sign language. Americans and British can understand each other under verbal communication since they share the common language English. But BSL(British Sign Langauge) and ASL separate and distinct languages that the speaker of ASL cannot fully understand BSL and vice versa. Even fingerspelling is different in that ASL uses one hand while BSL uses two hands.  This signifies that sign languages do not represent spoken languages and is highly influenced by the geographical locations and lines it develops. %0a%0a%0aReference%0ahttps://www.startasl.com/japanese-sign-language-jsl/#:~:text=Japanese%2520Sign%2520Language%2520(JSL)%2520is,not%2520mouthing%2520to%2520this%2520extent.%0ahttps://www.k-international.com/blog/different-types-of-sign-language-around-the-world/%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a#foxbegin 210509-034348-971350#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Some concrete characteristics of different sign languages %0a-> - ruiranx%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aI was curious about how fingerspelling differed between different sign languages, so I took a bit of a dive. Below is a smattering of different languages from an article I found [1].%0a%0a1. American Sign Language (ASL), as mentioned in Kyuwon's article, is a one-handed fingerspelling language, but lexical signing (where signs communicate words) is two-handed.%0a%0a2. British Sign Language (BSL), as also mentioned above, is primarily a two-handed fingerspelling language, but there also exists a secondary one-handed fingerspelling system (which originated in Ireland).%0a%0a3. Japanese Sign Language (JSL) has manual representations for not only hiragana (one of the Japanese lettering systems) but also for lexical units. It is apparently one of the younger sign languages [2], and notably makes use of mouthing.%0a%0a4. Dutch Sign Language (DSL) is considered a "mouth-hand system", and the signs used are much more "iconic" in that they resemble the lexical units being described. DSL's usage of mouthing was proven to be an integral part of the language as opposed to being a complementary facet; research showed that mouthing was actually contrastive in the language.%0a%0a[1] https://www.lifeprint.com/asl101/topics/signlanguagediversity3.htm%0a%0a[2] http://www.deaflibrary.org/jsl.html%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210509-034348-971350#%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a(:section: D:)%0a(:Category: Sign Language:)
